04629nam a22008175i 9780813553122DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2011028852  a97808135531227 a10.36019/97808135531222doi  a(DE-B1597)530272  a(OCoLC)792684895  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aKF9635b.C53 2012 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a342.7308/22231 aClarke, Alan W, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRendition to Torture /cAlan W Clarke. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGenocide, Political Violence, Human Rights0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUniversally condemned and everywhere illegal, torture goes on in democracies as well as in dictatorships. Nonetheless, many Americans were surprised following the attacks of 9/11 at how easily the United States embraced torture as well as the supposedly lesser evil of cruel, inhuman, and degrading treatment. Nothing seemed extreme when it came to questioning real and imagined terrorists. Extraordinary rendition—sending people captured in the “war on terror” to nations long counted among the world’s worst human rights violators—hid from the public eye cruel and bloody interrogations. “Torture lite” or “torture without marks” became the norm for those in American custody. In Rendition to Torture, Alan W. Clarke explains how the United States adopted torture as a matter of official policy; how and why it turned to extraordinary rendition as a way to outsource more extreme, mutilating forms of torture; and outlines the steps the United States took to hide its abuses. Many adverse consequences attended American use of torture. False information gleaned from torture was used to justify the Iraq war, adding potency to the charge that the war was illegal under international law. Moreover, European nations and Canada aided, abetted, and became thoroughly enmeshed in U.S.-led torture and renditions, thereby spreading both the problem and the blame for this practice. Clarke offers an extended critique of these activities, placing them in historical and legal context as well as in transnational and comparative perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDeportationxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aDeportationxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aDetention of personsxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aDetention of personsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aExtraordinary renditionxUnited States. 0aExtraordinary renditionzUnited States. 0aExtraordinary rendition. 0aFalse imprisonmentxUnited States. 0aFalse imprisonmentzUnited States. 0aNational securityxUnited States. 0aNational securityzUnited States. 0aTorturexGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aTorturexGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aTorture. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355312240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813553122423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813553122/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK